{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"Included with: <b> σάρδιον</b>, τό, <br /> <b>the Sardian stone</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 110d, 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “de Lapidibus” 8, 23, 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus “Bellum Judaicum” 5.5.7, NT.Rev.4.3, +others, “PHolm.” 3.36 \">NT+5th c.BC+</a>]; as a seal, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 22.1408.9 (4th c.BC), “Inscription Délos” 442 B 3 (2nd c.BC)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; σάρδια, of female ornaments, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 320.13, compare 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus 373.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]—This stone was of two kinds, the transparent-red or female being our <b>carnelian</b>, the transparent-brown or male our <b>sardine</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “de Lapidibus” 30 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]:—later λίθος <u>σάρδιος</u>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.AD: Philoponus, Joannes Philosophus \">Refs 6th c.AD+</a>] in “de An.” 321.10 (<i>plural</i>); <b>σάρδινος</b> λ., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Anecdota Graeca - MSS. Bibl. Oxon.” 4.229\">Refs</a>]; <b>σαρδόνιον</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.AD(?): Hesychius Legal icographus see at {σαρδώ}. \">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G9057","accentedUnicode":"σάρδιος","shortDef":"a carnelian","mediumDef":"a carnelian","stepGloss":"a carnelian","stepTransliteration":"sardios","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}